The eigenpair 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda,\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 satisfies the equation 
\begin_inset Formula $A\mathbf{v}=\lambda\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

, which can be solved for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

.
 Letting 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}=\left[\begin{array}{c}
v_{1}\\
v_{2}
\end{array}\right]$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\left[\begin{array}{cc}
-4 & 2\\
-16 & 8
\end{array}\right]\left[\begin{array}{c}
v_{1}\\
v_{2}
\end{array}\right] & =0\left[\begin{array}{c}
v_{1}\\
v_{2}
\end{array}\right]\\
\left[\begin{array}{c}
-4v_{1}+2v_{2}\\
-16v_{1}+8v_{2}
\end{array}\right] & =\left[\begin{array}{c}
0\\
0
\end{array}\right]
\end{align*}

\end_inset

so 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{2}$
\end_inset

 must satisfy the system
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
-4v_{1}+2v_{2} & =0\\
-16v_{1}+8v_{2} & =0
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Solving the first equation for 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{2}$
\end_inset

 as an attempt to solve the system by substitution: 
\begin_inset Formula $2v_{2}=4v_{1}$
\end_inset

 so 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{2}=2v_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 Substituting into the second equation, 
\begin_inset Formula $-16v_{1}+8(2v_{1})=0$
\end_inset

 yields 
\begin_inset Formula $0=0$
\end_inset

, a true statement for all values of 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{1}$
\end_inset

! This means 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{1}$
\end_inset

 can be anything and 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{2}$
\end_inset

 must be 
\begin_inset Formula $2v_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 For example,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[\begin{array}{c}
1\\
2
\end{array}\right]\text{ is an eigenvector}
\]

\end_inset

but any vector of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\begin{array}{c}
r\\
2r
\end{array}\right]$
\end_inset

