The question can be rephrased as a question about a linear system.
 By definition, the linear independence of the set hinges of the nature
 of the solutions of
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
a\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
1 & 8 & -11\end{array}\right]+b\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
9 & 4 & -7\end{array}\right]+c\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
4 & -2 & 2\end{array}\right]=\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
0 & 0 & 0\end{array}\right].\label{eq:sol-lin-ind-5}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This equation can be rewritten using algebra:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
a & 8a & -11a\end{array}\right]+\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
9b & 4b & -7b\end{array}\right]+\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
4c & -2c & 2c\end{array}\right] & =\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
0 & 0 & 0\end{array}\right]\\
\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
a+9b+4c & 8a+4b-2c & -11a-7b+2c\end{array}\right] & =\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
0 & 0 & 0\end{array}\right]
\end{align*}

\end_inset

The only way for this last equation to be true is if 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b,c$
\end_inset

 solve the linear system
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{array}{ccccccc}
a & + & 9b & + & 4c & = & 0\\
8a & + & 4b & - & 2c & = & 0\\
-11a & - & 7b & + & 2c & = & 0
\end{array}.\label{eq:sol-lin-ind-4}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

By row reduction,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[\begin{array}{cccc}
1 & 9 & 4 & 0\\
8 & 4 & -2 & 0\\
-11 & -7 & 2 & 0
\end{array}\right]\rightarrow\left[\begin{array}{cccc}
1 & 9 & 4 & 0\\
0 & -68 & -34 & 0\\
0 & -92 & 46 & 0
\end{array}\right]\rightarrow\left[\begin{array}{cccc}
1 & 9 & 4 & 0\\
0 & 2 & 1 & 0\\
0 & 2 & -1 & 0
\end{array}\right]\rightarrow\left[\begin{array}{cccc}
1 & 9 & 4 & 0\\
0 & 2 & 1 & 0\\
0 & 0 & -2 & 0
\end{array}\right]
\]

\end_inset

At this point, it is clear that the system has no free variables.
 Therefore part (vii) of theorem 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "thm:Matrix-Characterization-1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 is false.
 The equivalent part (iii) is therefore true, so (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:sol-lin-ind-4"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) has only the trivial solution.
 In turn, the trivial solution is the only solution of (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:sol-lin-ind-5"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

), so the set is linearly independent.
\end_layout

