\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 be an element of the codomain and suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $T(f_{1})=b$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $T(f_{2})=b$
\end_inset

, which is to say the equation 
\begin_inset Formula $T(a)=b$
\end_inset

 has more than one solution.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $T(f_{1})=T(f_{2})$
\end_inset

 so 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{x}f_{1}(x)=e^{x}f_{2}(x)$
\end_inset

.
 Dividing both sides of the equation by 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{x}$
\end_inset

, we find that 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}(x)=f_{2}(x)$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, in fact the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

two solutions
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 must actually be one and the same (and we have shown that the equation
 
\begin_inset Formula $T(a)=b$
\end_inset

 has at most one solution).
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

