The definitions of one-to-one and onto depend on the possible numbers of
 solutions of the equation 
\begin_inset Formula $T(a)=b$
\end_inset

, which in this case is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left[\begin{array}{cc}
14 & -1\\
-15 & 15\\
12 & 9
\end{array}\right]\left[\begin{array}{c}
a_{1}\\
a_{2}
\end{array}\right]=\left[\begin{array}{c}
b_{1}\\
b_{2}\\
b_{3}
\end{array}\right]\label{eq:isomorphisms-sol-3}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

(i) By theorem 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "thm:Matrix-Characterization-1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:isomorphisms-sol-3"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) has at most one solution for each 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 precisely if the columns of the coefficient matrix are linearly independent.
 By inspection, we can see that they are (they are not multiples of one
 another), so 
\begin_inset Formula $T(a)=b$
\end_inset

 has at most one solution for each 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 in the codomain and 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is one-to-one.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

(ii) By theorem 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "thm:Matrix-Characterization-2"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:isomorphisms-sol-3"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) has at least one solution for each 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 precisely if the coefficient matrix has a pivot position in every row.
 This is, however impossible since there are 3 rows and at most 2 pivot
 positions, one for each column.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $T(a)=b$
\end_inset

 has no solution for some elements 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 of the codomain and 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is not onto.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

(iii) No.
 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is not onto and therefore is not an isomorphism.
