Given any vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 in a vector space, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}-\mathbf{v}=\mathbf{0}$
\end_inset

 so
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\left\langle \mathbf{0},\mathbf{v}\right\rangle =\left\langle \mathbf{v}-\mathbf{v},\mathbf{v}\right\rangle  & \quad\text{by substituion}\\
=\left\langle \mathbf{v},\mathbf{v}\right\rangle +\left\langle -\mathbf{v},\mathbf{v}\right\rangle  & \quad\text{by inner product property 4}\\
=\left\langle \mathbf{v},\mathbf{v}\right\rangle +\left\langle (-1)\mathbf{v},\mathbf{v}\right\rangle  & \quad\text{by exercise \ref{exc:vector-spaces-29} of section \ref{sec:Vector-Spaces-and-Span}}\\
=\left\langle \mathbf{v},\mathbf{v}\right\rangle +(-1)\left\langle \mathbf{v},\mathbf{v}\right\rangle  & \quad\text{by inner product property 5}\\
=\left\langle \mathbf{v},\mathbf{v}\right\rangle -\left\langle \mathbf{v},\mathbf{v}\right\rangle =0 & \quad\text{by algebra of real numbers}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Hence 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \mathbf{0},\mathbf{v}\right\rangle =0$
\end_inset

 and by inner product property 3, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \mathbf{v},\mathbf{0}\right\rangle =\left\langle \mathbf{0},\mathbf{v}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 (which of course is zero).
\end_layout

